ALKAHEST BUILD LOG — PHASE 2
Platform Migration, Marauder Integration, and Strategic Pivot
Session Dates: April 10-12, 2026
1. SESSION OVERVIEW
This phase covers three days of work following the initial Alkahest Zero W build (Phase 1). The primary goals were to get Marauder fully operational via serial communication, migrate the platform from the Pi Zero W to the Pi 5 for improved performance, and make a reasoned decision about Marauder's role in the OT-Quest lab. The session involved significant troubleshooting, architecture pivots, and deliberate scope management.
2. ARCHITECTURE EVOLUTION
Phase 1 architecture (Pi Zero W)
Tablet -> SSH -> Alkahest hotspot (Pi Zero W) -> USB serial -> Marauder (ESP32)
Limitation discovered: Pi Zero W (2017, single-core ARMv6, 512MB RAM) could not run Kismet due to resource constraints. ESP32 hot-plug caused USB brown-out reboots. Serial communication via minicom suffered from lag and port re-enumeration instability.
Phase 2 architecture (Pi 5)
PC/Tablet -> SSH -> Pi 5 (Raspberry Pi OS) -> USB serial -> Marauder (ESP32)
Pi 5 (quad-core, 4GB RAM) provides stable USB power delivery, sufficient RAM for Kismet, and full desktop environment. Wired ethernet for internet, no hotspot required for lab use. ESP32 connects via USB with stable serial communication.
3. ISSUES ENCOUNTERED AND RESOLUTIONS
Issue: ESP32 hot-plug caused Pi Zero W reboots
Root cause: Pi Zero W USB port insufficient power delivery for ESP32 under load
Symptom: Multiple /dev/ttyUSB* ghost devices accumulating, not true brown-outs (HDMI never dipped)
Resolution: Migrated to Pi 5 with proper USB power delivery
Issue: Kali Linux ARM image corruption
Root cause: Known bug in Raspberry Pi Imager v2.0.0-2.0.7 causing SHA256 hash mismatch on download
Additional issue: Kali ARM64 image for Pi 5 not available as standalone download — imager only
Additional issue: armhf image downloaded instead of arm64 — wrong architecture for Pi 5
Resolution: Switched to Raspberry Pi OS (Trixie/Bookworm 64-bit) as base OS, install required tools manually
Issue: USB dongle boot order interference
Root cause: Pi 5 boot order prioritized USB-MSD over SD card when USB keyboard/mouse dongle present at power-on
Resolution: Insert SD card before plugging in USB dongle at boot
Issue: Kismet installation failure
Root cause: Pi OS Trixie uses sqv for GPG verification, deprecated apt-key method fails
Secondary issue: Kismet signing key 404 URL changed, required curl method instead of wget
Tertiary issue: apt install stalled on slow Kismet servers — required direct .deb approach
Final working installation method:
curl -s https://www.kismetwireless.net/repos/kismet-release.gpg.key | gpg --dearmor | sudo tee /usr/share/keyrings/kismet-archive-keyring.gpg > /dev/null && echo 'deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/kismet-archive-keyring.gpg] https://www.kismetwireless.net/repos/apt/release/trixie trixie main' | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kismet.list && sudo apt update && sudo apt install kismet -y
Issue: Marauder serial communication lag and unresponsiveness
Root cause: Generic WROOM dev board CP210x USB-serial chip re-enumerates under load
minicom and screen both struggled with Marauder's streaming output model
Solution found: Python pyserial with threading for continuous output reading
scanap confirmed working — returned live SSID/BSSID/channel/signal data from surrounding environment
4. MARAUDER PYTHON INTERFACE SCRIPT
Saved as ~/marauder.py on the Pi 5. Run with: python3 ~/marauder.py
import serial
import time
import threading

s = serial.Serial('/dev/ttyUSB0', 115200, timeout=1)
print('Connected to Marauder. Type commands (quit to exit):')

def read_output():
    while True:
        if s.in_waiting:
            print(s.read(s.in_waiting).decode('utf-8', errors='ignore'), end='')
        time.sleep(0.1)

t = threading.Thread(target=read_output, daemon=True)
t.start()

while True:
    cmd = input()
    if cmd == 'quit':
        break
    s.write((cmd + '\r\n').encode())

s.close()
5. CONFIRMED WORKING MARAUDER COMMANDS
scanap — scans for Wi-Fi access points. Returns RSSI, channel, BSSID, SSID, encryption flags
stopscan — stops any active scan
help — lists all available commands
scansta — scans for client stations (requires passive listening period, 30-60 seconds)
