6. HOW TO READ SCANAP OUTPUT
Format: [RSSI] Ch: [channel] [BSSID] ESSID: [network name] [encryption] [flags]
RSSI (e.g. -81) — signal strength in dBm. Closer to 0 is stronger. -50 is strong, -90 is weak
Ch — WiFi channel (1-13 for 2.4GHz, higher for 5GHz)
BSSID — the router's MAC address. This is publicly broadcast by design, not private information
ESSID — the network name (SSID)
11/31 — encryption flags (11 = WEP, 31 = WPA/WPA2)
7. STRATEGIC DECISION — MARAUDER DEPRIORITIZED
After four days of work, a deliberate decision was made to deprioritize Marauder integration and focus the Pi 5 platform on OT-relevant tools. This was not a failure — it was a reasoned engineering decision.
What Marauder does
Deauth attacks (802.11 management frame injection)
Beacon spam (fake SSID flooding)
PMKID capture (offline WPA2 cracking)
Bluetooth scanning and device enumeration
What the OT-Quest lab actually needs
Kismet — detecting unauthorized wireless near ICS infrastructure
Nmap — network discovery and device enumeration on Modbus TCP networks
Wireshark — Modbus TCP packet capture and protocol analysis
Python serial — communicating with PLCs and industrial devices
Conclusion
Marauder is an offensive wireless tool. The OT-Quest mission is defensive ICS security. Marauder is documented, understood, and functional — it serves the portfolio. But further time chasing serial interface issues with a generic dev board has diminishing returns versus the OT-focused toolchain. The $7 dedicated Marauder screen or a proper web UI (marauder-ui or custom Flask) remains a future option when the ROI makes sense.
